b'Rural Health Professions Summer Preceptorship'
b'Home'
b'Education'
b'Programs for High School and College Students'
b'caherman'
b'The Rural Health Professions Summer Preceptorship for College Students'
b'The Rural Health Professions Summer Preceptorship for College Students is a rural immersion program for health professions students. It is a six-week, paid, full-time experience.'
b'June 10 \xe2\x80\x93 July 23, 2019 SSM Health St. Mary\xe2\x80\x99s Hospital \xe2\x80\x93 Centralia Centralia, IL'
b'June 12 \xe2\x80\x93 July 24, 2019 Gibson Area Hospital Gibson City, IL'
b'The Preceptorship program is a full-time opportunity set in two rural communities in Illinois: Gibson City and Centralia. Four students are selected for each site and spend each week shadowing different healthcare professionals within the community.'
b'Students work together in weekly classroom sessions and for their Community Service Learning (CSL) project, which is the culminating experience of the program and allows students to apply their understanding of healthcare to a real-life community health priority.'
b'The experience is designed to:'
b''
b'Eligible Health Professions Disciplines'
b'Health professions students must have at least completed their sophomore year of undergraduate training and demonstrate an interest in rural health care. \xe2\x80\xa2 Medicine \xe2\x80\xa2 Pharmacy \xe2\x80\xa2 Nursing \xe2\x80\xa2 Public Health \xe2\x80\xa2 Social Work \xe2\x80\xa2 Physician Assistant \xe2\x80\xa2 Physical Therapy \xe2\x80\xa2 Nutrition \xe2\x80\xa2 Speech & Language Pathology \xe2\x80\xa2 Other health professions as appropriate'
b'A\xc2\xa0Typical Six-Week Rural Experience'
b'Participation in all activities is mandatory and students must have their own transportation.'
b'Community Service Learning Project'
b'The Community Service Learning (CSL) Project is an integral part of the preceptorship. The purpose of the CSL is to emphasize the community context of health care. The project is decided on by the host site and benefits the larger community. Students spend at least one day a week working on the project which is guided by faculty and community preceptors. Below is a list of some of the previous projects completed by students:'
b'To apply'
b'Health professions students who have completed sophomore year by the start of the program as well as graduate and professional-level students are eligible to apply.'
b'The following documents are required to apply:'
b'(www.ncrhp.uic.edu under student opportunities)'
b'Applications are not considered complete until all materials and fee have been received. Applications are due Sunday, February 17, 2019.'
b'For More Information'
b'Vicky Rhine, MPH University of Illinois College of Medicine Rockford National Center for Rural Health Professions P: (815) 395-5854 E: rhine1@uic.edu www.ncrhp.uic.edu'
b'rhine1@uic.edu'
